    "After twenty years in our home, my wife and I had built up $210,000 in equity. We were also carrying $26,000 in credit card debt from various life events — a job loss, a medical procedure, car repairs. We'd accepted the debt as 'just the way it is.' Then our accountant showed us the numbers: we were paying $5,700 a year in credit card interest while sitting on $210,000 in equity earning us nothing. The HELOC cut our interest costs by $3,800 a year.",
    "I ran into a friend I hadn't seen in two years. He looked relaxed, happy — completely different from the stressed-out guy I remembered. I asked what changed. He said, 'I got a HELOC and consolidated everything. My monthly payments dropped by $600 and I can actually breathe.' He explained the whole process — fifteen-minute application, no closing costs, approved in a week. I applied the next day. He was right. Same debt, same income, and I could finally breathe too.",
    "The breaking point for me was when my air conditioning died in July. Quote to replace: $9,500. My savings: $2,200. Credit card space: maybe $5,000 at 24% APR. I was going to finance a necessity at credit card rates in the middle of summer with two kids at home. My wife's friend mentioned a HELOC almost casually: 'Just draw from your equity. That's what we did for our roof last year.' Two weeks later, I had a $60,000 HELOC. Drew $9,500 for the AC. Monthly payment: $59. On a credit card, that same $9,500 would've cost me $190/month. I saved $131 a month on an air conditioner.",
    "I was skeptical about HELOCs because I thought it meant putting my house at risk. Then I talked to a loan officer who explained it simply: 'You're already leveraging your house — that's your mortgage. A HELOC is just a second, smaller layer of borrowing against equity you've already built. The risk isn't taking a HELOC — the risk is paying 22% interest on credit cards when 7% money is available to you.' When she put it that way, the risk of NOT getting a HELOC seemed far greater.",
    "My brother and I both inherited debt from our parents' estate — about $30,000 each in various obligations. He put his on a personal loan at 11%. I used my HELOC at 7.5%. Same debt. Same starting point. Three years later, he's paid $40,200 total. I've paid $36,750. I saved $3,450 on the same $30,000 debt simply because of where I borrowed. He's still upset about it.",
    "I work in accounting, so I ran every number before getting a HELOC. The results were so clearly in favor that I felt embarrassed I hadn't done it years earlier. $42,000 in credit card debt at 21% average = $8,820/year in interest. Same $42,000 on a HELOC at 7.5% = $3,150/year. Annual savings: $5,670. Five-year savings: $28,350. That's not a rounding error — that's a car. That's a year of college tuition. That's money I was lighting on fire every single year.",
